description:
Black-eyed Susan (Rudbeckia hirta)

22 May 2016
Ray Roberts Lake State Park, Isle Du Bois
Pilot Point, Denton County, Texas

A wildflower native to North America, Black-eyed Susan is known by additional common names including Common Black-eyed Susan and Brown-eyed Susan. The range map presented by the Plants Database of the US Department of Agriculture indicates that with the exception of two states in the United States (Arizona and Nevada), this native wildflower is found in every other state from one end of the continent to the other. The same is true for Canada, where Black-eyed Susan is found in every province excepting their most northern areas where it apparently doesn't take well to the cold. Black-eyed Susan has been introduced into Alaska as well. While not indicated in this range map, it's most likely that Black-eyed Susan occurs in some parts of northern Mexico. Because of its transcontinental range in North America, Black-eyed Susan is an authentic resident of the Western Hemisphere. Ray Roberts Lake State Park, Isle Du Bois, is administered by the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department.

Sources:

"Rudbeckia hirta," Native Plant Database, Lady Bird Johnson Wildflower Center, University of Texas at Austin, description, photographs, classification, resources, accessed 5.24.16, http://www.wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=RUHI2

Rudbeckia hirta

Rudbeckia hirta L.

Black-eyed Susan, Common black-eyed Susan, Brown-eyed Susan

Asteraceae (Aster Family)

Synonym(s):

USDA Symbol: ruhi2

USDA Native Status: L48 (N), AK (I), CAN (N)

This cheerful, widespread wildflower is considered an annual to a short-lived perennial across its range. Bright-yellow, 2-3 in. wide, daisy-like flowers with dark centers are its claim-to-fame. They occur singly atop 1-2 ft. stems. The stems and scattered, oval leaves are covered with bristly hairs. Coarse, rough-stemmed plant with daisy-like flower heads made up of showy golden-yellow ray flowers, with disk flowers forming a brown central cone.

This native prairie biennial forms a rosette of leaves the first year, followed by flowers the second year. It is covered with hairs that give it a slightly rough texture. The Green-headed Coneflower (R. laciniata) has yellow ray flowers pointing downward, a greenish-yellow disk, and irregularly divided leaves.
